# Refined Solution
### Problem Statement Explanation  
A rigid, horizontal disk of radius \(2R\) spins with a constant angular velocity  

\[
\boldsymbol{\Omega}= \omega\,\hat{\mathbf k},\qquad \omega>0 ,
\]

about the vertical axis through its centre \(O\) ( \(\hat{\mathbf k}\) points out of the disk).  

A bug of mass \(m\) stays in contact with the upper surface of the disk.  In the frame that is rigidly attached to the disk (the ‚Äúrotating frame‚Äù):

‚Ä¢ The bug‚Äôs trajectory is a circle of radius \(R\).  
‚Ä¢ The centre of that circle is at a distance \(R\) from \(O\).  
‚Ä¢ The bug‚Äôs angular speed round this circle equals the disk‚Äôs angular speed and has the same sense:  

\[
\dot{\varphi}= \omega .
\]

Gravity is neglected, so the only real force on the bug is the contact force \(\mathbf F\) exerted by the disk.  
Our task is to find the maximum magnitude \(F_{\max}\) of this force that is required to keep the prescribed motion.

Throughout the solution:

‚Ä¢ Symbols without a sub-script refer to the inertial laboratory frame \(OXYZ\).  
‚Ä¢ Symbols carrying the sub-script ‚Äúrel‚Äô‚Äô refer to measurements in the rotating frame fixed to the disk.  
‚Ä¢ Unit vectors \(\hat{\mathbf i}_{\rm rot},\hat{\mathbf j}_{\rm rot},\hat{\mathbf k}\) are fixed in that rotating frame, and \(\hat{\mathbf k}\) is common to both frames.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

### Step 1  
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions  
\[
\boxed{\mathbf a = \mathbf a_{\rm rel}+2\;\boldsymbol{\Omega}\!\times\!\mathbf v_{\rm rel}
       +\boldsymbol{\Omega}\!\times(\boldsymbol{\Omega}\!\times\!\mathbf r)}
\]

(The term \(\dot{\boldsymbol{\Omega}}\times\mathbf r\) is absent because \(\dot{\boldsymbol{\Omega}}=0\).)

Derivation  
\[
\begin{align}
\dot{\boldsymbol{\Omega}}=0
\quad\Longrightarrow\quad
\mathbf a
   =\mathbf a_{\rm rel}+2\,\boldsymbol{\Omega}\times\mathbf v_{\rm rel}
     +\boldsymbol{\Omega}\times\bigl(\boldsymbol{\Omega}\times\mathbf r\bigr).
\label{eq:kin} \tag{1}
\end{align}
\]

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

### Step 2  
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions  
\[
\boxed{(\mathbf r-\mathbf c)\!\cdot\!(\mathbf r-\mathbf c)=R^{2}}
\]

Derivation  
\[
\begin{align}
\text{Choose the centre of the crawling circle as }
      \mathbf c &= R\,\hat{\mathbf i}_{\rm rot},\nonumber\\
\varphi(t) &= \omega t,\qquad \varphi=0\ \text{when the bug is at the rim}\,(r=2R).
\nonumber
\end{align}
\]
Hence the position of the bug in the rotating frame is  
\[
\begin{align}
\mathbf r_{\rm rot}(t)
      &=\mathbf c
        +R\bigl(\cos\varphi\,\hat{\mathbf i}_{\rm rot}
               +\sin\varphi\,\hat{\mathbf j}_{\rm rot}\bigr)\nonumber\\
      &=R\Bigl[(1+\cos\varphi)\,\hat{\mathbf i}_{\rm rot}
               +\sin\varphi\,\hat{\mathbf j}_{\rm rot}\Bigr].
\label{eq:r} \tag{2}
\end{align}
\]

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

### Step 3  
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions  
\[
\boxed{\mathbf v_{\rm rel}= \dfrac{d\mathbf r_{\rm rot}}{dt}},\qquad
\boxed{\mathbf a_{\rm rel}= \dfrac{d\mathbf v_{\rm rel}}{dt}}
\]

Derivation  
\[
\begin{align}
\mathbf v_{\rm rel}
   &=\frac{d}{dt}\Bigl[R\bigl(\cos\varphi\,\hat{\mathbf i}_{\rm rot}
                              +\sin\varphi\,\hat{\mathbf j}_{\rm rot}\bigr)\Bigr]\nonumber\\
   &=R\dot{\varphi}\bigl(-\sin\varphi\,\hat{\mathbf i}_{\rm rot}
                         +\cos\varphi\,\hat{\mathbf j}_{\rm rot}\bigr)\nonumber\\
   &=R\omega\bigl(-\sin\varphi\,\hat{\mathbf i}_{\rm rot}
                  +\cos\varphi\,\hat{\mathbf j}_{\rm rot}\bigr),
\label{eq:vrel} \tag{3}\\[6pt]
\mathbf a_{\rm rel}
   &=\frac{d\mathbf v_{\rm rel}}{dt}
   =-\omega^{2}R\bigl(\cos\varphi\,\hat{\mathbf i}_{\rm rot}
                      +\sin\varphi\,\hat{\mathbf j}_{\rm rot}\bigr).
\label{eq:arel} \tag{4}
\end{align}
\]

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

### Step 4  
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions  
\[
\boxed{\mathbf a_{\rm Cor}=2\,\boldsymbol{\Omega}\!\times\!\mathbf v_{\rm rel}},\qquad
\boxed{\mathbf a_{\rm cen}= \boldsymbol{\Omega}\!\times(\boldsymbol{\Omega}\!\times\!\mathbf r)
                           = -\omega^{2}\mathbf r}
\]

Derivation  
\[
\begin{align}
\mathbf a_{\rm Cor}
   &=2\omega\hat{\mathbf k}\times
     \Bigl[R\omega\bigl(-\sin\varphi\,\hat{\mathbf i}_{\rm rot}
                        +\cos\varphi\,\hat{\mathbf j}_{\rm rot}\bigr)\Bigr]\nonumber\\
   &=-2\omega^{2}R\bigl(\cos\varphi\,\hat{\mathbf i}_{\rm rot}
                        +\sin\varphi\,\hat{\mathbf j}_{\rm rot}\bigr),
\label{eq:aCor} \tag{5}\\[6pt]
\mathbf a_{\rm cen}
   &=-\omega^{2}\,\mathbf r_{\rm rot}
   =-\omega^{2}R\Bigl[(1+\cos\varphi)\,\hat{\mathbf i}_{\rm rot}
                      +\sin\varphi\,\hat{\mathbf j}_{\rm rot}\Bigr].
\label{eq:acen} \tag{6}
\end{align}
\]

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

### Step 5  
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions  
\[
\boxed{\mathbf a
       =\mathbf a_{\rm rel}+\mathbf a_{\rm Cor}+\mathbf a_{\rm cen}}
\]

Derivation  
\[
\begin{align}
\mathbf a
 &=\Bigl[-\omega^{2}R\bigl(\cos\varphi\,\hat{\mathbf i}_{\rm rot}
                            +\sin\varphi\,\hat{\mathbf j}_{\rm rot}\bigr)\Bigr]
      \tag{4}\\
 &\quad+\Bigl[-2\omega^{2}R\bigl(\cos\varphi\,\hat{\mathbf i}_{\rm rot}
                                  +\sin\varphi\,\hat{\mathbf j}_{\rm rot}\bigr)\Bigr]
      \tag{5}\\
 &\quad+\Bigl[-\omega^{2}R\bigl((1+\cos\varphi)\,\hat{\mathbf i}_{\rm rot}
                                 +\sin\varphi\,\hat{\mathbf j}_{\rm rot}\bigr)\Bigr]
      \tag{6}\\[6pt]
 &= -\omega^{2}R\Bigl[(4\cos\varphi+1)\,\hat{\mathbf i}_{\rm rot}
                      +4\sin\varphi\,\hat{\mathbf j}_{\rm rot}\Bigr].
\label{eq:a} \tag{7}
\end{align}
\]

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

### Step 6  
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions  
\[
\boxed{|\mathbf a|=\sqrt{a_x^{2}+a_y^{2}}},\qquad
\boxed{\displaystyle\max_{-1\le\cos\varphi\le 1}(17+8\cos\varphi)=25}
\]

Derivation  
\[
\begin{align}
|\mathbf a|^{2}
 &=\omega^{4}R^{2}\Bigl[(4\cos\varphi+1)^{2}+(4\sin\varphi)^{2}\Bigr]\nonumber\\
 &=\omega^{4}R^{2}\Bigl[16\cos^{2}\varphi+8\cos\varphi+1
                        +16\sin^{2}\varphi\Bigr]\nonumber\\
 &=\omega^{4}R^{2}\bigl(17+8\cos\varphi\bigr).
\label{eq:a2} \tag{8}
\end{align}
\]
Because \(-1\le\cos\varphi\le 1\), the right-hand side is maximised when \(\cos\varphi = 1\) (\(\varphi = 0\)). Therefore  

\[
\begin{align}
a_{\max}
   &=\omega^{2}R\sqrt{25} = 5\omega^{2}R.
\label{eq:amax} \tag{9}
\end{align}
\]

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

### Step 7  
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions  
\[
\boxed{\mathbf F = m\,\mathbf a}
\]

Derivation  
\[
\begin{align}
F_{\max}
  &=m\,a_{\max}
  =m\,(5\omega^{2}R)
  =5\,m\,\omega^{2}R.
\label{eq:Fmax} \tag{10}
\end{align}
\]

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

### Final Answer  
\[
\begin{align}
\boxed{F_{\max}=5\,m\,\omega^{2}R}
\end{align}
\]

# Refined Solution

### Problem Statement Explanation
We consider a deuteron, i.e. a bound two-body system consisting of one proton and one neutron.  
Because the proton mass \(m_{p}\) and the neutron mass \(m_{n}\) are almost equal, we shall denote their common value by  
\(M \simeq m_{p} \simeq m_{n}\).  
In the centre‚Äìof‚Äìmass frame the relative motion of the two nucleons is equivalent to the motion of a single particle of reduced mass  

\[
\mu=\frac{M}{2}.
\]

According to Yukawa, nuclear forces with a massive propagator (here the \(\pi\)-meson of mass \(m\)) can be described by the attractive potential  

\[
U(r)=-\frac{A\,e^{-r/\lambda}}{r},\qquad 
\lambda=\frac{h}{2\pi m c}.
\]

Here  
‚Ä¢ \(r\)  ‚Ä¶ separation of the nucleons,  
‚Ä¢ \(A>0\) ‚Ä¶ coupling constant of the strong force,  
‚Ä¢ \(c\)  ‚Ä¶ speed of light,  
‚Ä¢ \(h\)  ‚Ä¶ Planck constant.

We assume the nucleons execute nearly circular motion of radius \(r\) and perform small radial oscillations about this circular orbit.  
The task is to find the total azimuthal angle \(\varphi\) swept by the line joining the two nucleons during one complete, infinitesimal-amplitude radial oscillation.

No relativity or dissipative effects are taken into account; Newtonian mechanics is adequate.

---

### Step 1
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions  
\[\boxed{U(r)=-\dfrac{A\,e^{-r/\lambda}}{r}}\]  
\[\boxed{V_{\mathrm{eff}}(r)=U(r)+\dfrac{L^{2}}{2\mu r^{2}}}\]

Derivation  
\[
\begin{align}
\text{Condition for a circular orbit:}\quad
\frac{dV_{\mathrm{eff}}}{dr}\Big|_{r}=0
&\;\Longrightarrow\;
\frac{dU}{dr}\Big|_{r}-\frac{L^{2}}{\mu r^{3}}=0, \\[4pt]
\therefore\;
L^{2}
&=\mu r^{3}\,U'(r).
\label{eq:Lsq}\tag{1}
\end{align}
\]

---

### Step 2
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions  
\[\boxed{F(r)=-\dfrac{dU}{dr}}\]  
\[\boxed{\mu\,\omega_{\phi}^{2}r=\bigl|F(r)\bigr|}\]

Derivation  
\[
\begin{align}
U'(r)
&=\frac{d}{dr}\!\left[-\frac{A e^{-r/\lambda}}{r}\right]
  =A e^{-r/\lambda}\!\left(\frac{1}{r^{2}}+\frac{1}{\lambda r}\right),\\
\bigl|F(r)\bigr|
&=-U'(r)=A e^{-r/\lambda}\!\left(\frac{1}{r^{2}}+\frac{1}{\lambda r}\right),\\
\mu\,\omega_{\phi}^{2}r
&=\bigl|F(r)\bigr|
  \quad\Longrightarrow\quad
\omega_{\phi}^{2}
=\frac{A\,e^{-r/\lambda}}{\mu\,r^{3}}
 \bigl(1+\tfrac{r}{\lambda}\bigr).
\label{eq:omegaphi}\tag{2}
\end{align}
\]

---

### Step 3
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions  
\[\boxed{\omega_{r}^{2}=\dfrac{1}{\mu}\,
        \dfrac{d^{2}V_{\mathrm{eff}}}{dr^{2}}\Big|_{r}}\]

Derivation  
\[
\begin{align}
U''(r)
&=\frac{d}{dr}\Bigl[A e^{-r/\lambda}\bigl(r^{-2}+(\lambda r)^{-1}\bigr)\Bigr]
  =-A e^{-r/\lambda}\!\left(\frac{2}{\lambda r^{2}}
                            +\frac{1}{\lambda^{2}r}
                            +\frac{2}{r^{3}}\right),\\[4pt]
\frac{d^{2}}{dr^{2}}\Bigl(\frac{L^{2}}{2\mu r^{2}}\Bigr)
&=\frac{3L^{2}}{\mu r^{4}}
  =\frac{3U'(r)}{r}\quad\text{(by \eqref{eq:Lsq})},\\[4pt]
\frac{d^{2}V_{\mathrm{eff}}}{dr^{2}}\Big|_{r}
&=U''(r)+\frac{3U'(r)}{r}  \\[4pt]
&=A e^{-r/\lambda}\!\left(\frac{1}{r^{3}}
                          +\frac{1}{\lambda r^{2}}
                          -\frac{1}{\lambda^{2}r}\right),\\[6pt]
\therefore\;
\omega_{r}^{2}
&=\frac{A\,e^{-r/\lambda}}{\mu\,r^{3}}
  \left(1+\frac{r}{\lambda}-\frac{r^{2}}{\lambda^{2}}\right).
\label{eq:omegar}\tag{3}
\end{align}
\]

---

### Step 4
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions  
\[\boxed{\displaystyle 
\varphi
 = \omega_{\phi}T_{r}
 = \omega_{\phi}\frac{2\pi}{\omega_{r}}
 = 2\pi\frac{\omega_{\phi}}{\omega_{r}}
}\]

Derivation  
\[
\begin{align}
\frac{\omega_{\phi}^{2}}{\omega_{r}^{2}}
&=\frac{\,1+\tfrac{r}{\lambda}\,}
       {\,1+\tfrac{r}{\lambda}-\tfrac{r^{2}}{\lambda^{2}}\,},\\[8pt]
\therefore\;
\varphi
&=2\pi\sqrt{\frac{1+\tfrac{r}{\lambda}}
                   {1+\tfrac{r}{\lambda}-\tfrac{r^{2}}{\lambda^{2}}}}.
\label{eq:phi}\tag{4}
\end{align}
\]

---

### Final Answer
\[
\begin{align}
\boxed{\displaystyle
\varphi
 = 2\pi\,
   \sqrt{\frac{1+\dfrac{r}{\lambda}}
              {1+\dfrac{r}{\lambda}-\dfrac{r^{2}}{\lambda^{2}}}}
}
\end{align}
\]

Hence, during one complete (infinitesimal-amplitude) radial oscillation about an initially circular orbit of radius \(r\), the proton‚Äìneutron pair in a deuteron sweeps the above azimuthal angle \(\varphi\) in the centre-of-mass frame.

# Refined Solution
### Problem Statement Explanation
We study monochromatic, linearly-polarised, plane light of angular frequency œâ that propagates in the +x‚Äìdirection inside a uniform, isotropic, non-magnetic dielectric of refractive index n (>1).  
The experimentally observed law of (linear) absorption is

‚ÄÉdI/dx = ‚ÄìŒ± I,

where  
‚Ä¢ I(x) is the light intensity (time-averaged Poynting flux) at depth x,  
‚Ä¢ Œ± (>0) is the absorption (attenuation) coefficient to be determined.

Microscopic model of the medium (classical Lorentz oscillator):  
1. Each atom furnishes one effective electron of charge ‚Äìe, mass m; the atomic number density is N (m‚Åª¬≥).  
2. The electron is bound to its nucleus through a linear restoring force ‚Äìm œâ‚ÇÄ¬≤ x (œâ‚ÇÄ is the natural angular frequency); x(t) is the displacement measured from equilibrium.  
3. The electron also experiences a damping force ‚Äìm Œ≥ v (v ‚â° ·∫ã), assumed weak (Œ≥ ‚â™ œâ).  
4. Under the driving electric field E(t) of the incident wave the electron executes forced oscillations and re-radiates.  
5. The dominant interaction is due to the electric field; the magnetic part of the Lorentz force is smaller by v/c and is neglected (v ‚â™ c).  

Radiative energy loss of an accelerated charge (Larmor formula)

‚ÄÉP = e¬≤ ‚ü®a¬≤‚ü© / (6 œÄ Œµ‚ÇÄ c¬≥),

where ‚ü®a¬≤‚ü© is the time average over one optical period.

By balancing, for a thin slab of thickness dx, the power taken from the beam equals the total radiated power of the electrons inside that slab, we will obtain Œ±.

All symbols:  
Œµ‚ÇÄ ‚Äì vacuum permittivity; c ‚Äì speed of light in vacuum;  
x(t) ‚Äì displacement; v(t) ‚Äì velocity; a(t) ‚Äì acceleration;  
an over-bar (‚ü® ‚ü©) designates a time average over one optical period.

### Step 1
Principles / Original Formulas / Assumptions  
\[
\boxed{m\ddot{x} + m\gamma\dot{x} + m\omega_{0}^{2}x = -eE_{0}e^{i\omega t}}
\]

Derivation  
\[
\begin{align}
\text{Assume a steady-state solution }x(t)=\tilde x\,e^{i\omega t}. \label{eq:s1_ansatz}\tag{1}\\
\bigl(-m\omega^{2}+im\gamma\omega+m\omega_{0}^{2}\bigr)\tilde x &= -eE_{0}, \nonumber\\
\tilde x &= \frac{-eE_{0}/m}{\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2}+i\gamma\omega}. \label{eq:s1_xtilde}\tag{2}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 2
Principles / Original Formulas / Assumptions  
\[
\boxed{v(t)=\dot{x}(t)}, \qquad \boxed{a(t)=\dot{v}(t)}
\]

Derivation  
\[
\begin{align}
\tilde v &= i\omega \tilde x = \frac{-i\omega eE_{0}/m}{\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2}+i\gamma\omega}, \label{eq:s2_vtilde}\tag{3}\\
\tilde a &= i\omega \tilde v = -\omega^{2}\tilde x
        = \frac{\omega^{2} eE_{0}/m}{\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2}+i\gamma\omega}. \label{eq:s2_atilde}\tag{4}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 3
Principles / Original Formulas / Assumptions  
\[
\boxed{\left\langle\bigl(\operatorname{Re}\,A\,e^{i\omega t}\bigr)^{2}\right\rangle = \dfrac{|A|^{2}}{2}}
\]

Derivation  
\[
\begin{align}
\langle v^{2}\rangle &= \frac{|\tilde v|^{2}}{2}
                    = \frac{1}{2}\frac{(\omega eE_{0}/m)^{2}}
                                   {(\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2})^{2}+\gamma^{2}\omega^{2}}, \label{eq:s3_v2}\tag{5}\\[4pt]
\langle a^{2}\rangle &= \frac{|\tilde a|^{2}}{2}
                    = \frac{1}{2}\frac{(\omega^{2} eE_{0}/m)^{2}}
                                   {(\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2})^{2}+\gamma^{2}\omega^{2}}. \label{eq:s3_a2}\tag{6}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 4
Principles / Original Formulas / Assumptions  
\[
\boxed{P_{\text{rad}}=\dfrac{e^{2}\langle a^{2}\rangle}{6\pi\varepsilon_{0}c^{3}}},\qquad
\boxed{P_{\text{rad}} = m\gamma\,\langle v^{2}\rangle}
\]

Derivation  
\[
\begin{align}
m\gamma\,\langle v^{2}\rangle &= \frac{e^{2}\langle a^{2}\rangle}{6\pi\varepsilon_{0}c^{3}} \nonumber\\
\gamma &= \frac{e^{2}\omega^{2}}{6\pi\varepsilon_{0}m\,c^{3}}. \label{eq:s4_gamma}\tag{7}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 5
Principles / Original Formulas / Assumptions  
\[
\boxed{P_{\text{rad}} = m\gamma\,\langle v^{2}\rangle}
\]

Derivation  
\[
\begin{align}
P_{\text{rad}}
   &= m\gamma\langle v^{2}\rangle \nonumber\\
   &= m\!\left(\frac{e^{2}\omega^{2}}{6\pi\varepsilon_{0}m c^{3}}\right)
      \!\left[\frac{1}{2}\frac{(\omega eE_{0}/m)^{2}}
                         {(\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2})^{2}+\gamma^{2}\omega^{2}}\right] \nonumber\\
   &= \frac{e^{4}\omega^{4}E_{0}^{2}}
            {12\pi\varepsilon_{0}c^{3}m^{2}
             \bigl[(\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2})^{2}+\gamma^{2}\omega^{2}\bigr]}. \label{eq:s5_Prad}\tag{8}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 6
Principles / Original Formulas / Assumptions  
\[
\boxed{\frac{dI}{dx} = -N\,P_{\text{rad}}},\qquad
\boxed{\frac{dI}{dx} = -\alpha\,I}
\]

Derivation  
\[
\begin{align}
\alpha &= \frac{N\,P_{\text{rad}}}{I}. \label{eq:s6_alpha_def}\tag{9}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 7
Principles / Original Formulas / Assumptions  
\[
\boxed{I = \dfrac{1}{2}\,n\,\varepsilon_{0}\,c\,E_{0}^{2}}
\]

Derivation  
\[
\begin{align}
I = \frac{1}{2} n \varepsilon_{0} c \, E_{0}^{2}. \label{eq:s7_intensity}\tag{10}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 8
Principles / Original Formulas / Assumptions  
(no new universal principle; algebraic substitution of previous results)

Derivation  
\[
\begin{align}
\alpha
&= \frac{N}{\dfrac{1}{2} n \varepsilon_{0} c E_{0}^{2}}
      \left[\frac{e^{4}\omega^{4}E_{0}^{2}}
                 {12\pi\varepsilon_{0}c^{3}m^{2}
                 \bigl[(\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2})^{2}+\gamma^{2}\omega^{2}\bigr]}\right] \nonumber\\[6pt]
&= \frac{N\,e^{4}\,\omega^{4}}
        {6\pi\,n\,\varepsilon_{0}^{2}\,c^{4}\,m^{2}
         \bigl[(\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2})^{2}+\gamma^{2}\omega^{2}\bigr]}, \label{eq:s8_alpha}\tag{11}
\end{align}
\]
with Œ≥ from Eq. \eqref{eq:s4_gamma}.  Because Œ≥ ‚àù œâ¬≤, Œ±(œâ) may be written entirely in terms of fundamental constants if desired.

### Final Answer
\[
\begin{align}
\boxed{\displaystyle
\alpha(\omega)=
\frac{N\,e^{4}\,\omega^{4}}
     {6\pi\,n\,\varepsilon_{0}^{2}\,c^{4}\,m^{2}\,
      \Bigl[(\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2})^{2}
            +\Bigl(\dfrac{e^{2}\omega^{3}}{6\pi\varepsilon_{0}m\,c^{3}}\Bigr)^{2}\Bigr]}}
\end{align}
\]

This expression, obtained from the classical Lorentz-oscillator model together with the Larmor radiation formula, gives the absorption coefficient Œ± for a monochromatic wave of angular frequency œâ traversing a weakly absorbing dielectric medium of refractive index n and electron number density N.

# Refined Solution
### Problem Statement Explanation  
A solid, homogeneous sphere  

‚Ä¢ mass:‚ÄÉ\(m\)  
‚Ä¢ radius:‚ÄÉ\(R\)  
‚Ä¢ total charge:‚ÄÉ\(Q\) (uniformly distributed throughout the volume)  
‚Ä¢ rotation:‚ÄÉconstant angular velocity \(\boldsymbol\omega =\omega\,\hat{\mathbf z}\) about the vertical \(z\)-axis  

is located with its centre at a distance \(h\;(>R)\) above an infinitely large, perfectly superconducting (perfect diamagnetic) plate that coincides with the \(xy\)-plane (\(z=0\)).  

Physics of the situation  

1.  Gravity of magnitude \(mg\) acts in the \(-z\)-direction.  
2.  Because an ideal super-conductor behaves as a perfect conductor for electrostatics and exhibits the Meissner effect for magnetostatics, the ‚Äúimage‚Äù method may be used:  
    ‚Ä¢ an electrostatic image charge \(-Q\) at \((0,0,-h)\);  
    ‚Ä¢ a magnetic image dipole \(\boldsymbol\mu_{\text{im}}=-\boldsymbol\mu\) at \((0,0,-h)\).  
3.  In the equilibrium (levitating) state the sphere‚Äôs centre is at rest; hence the net vertical force must vanish:  
   upward magnetic repulsion = downward electrostatic attraction + weight.  

The goal is to determine the equilibrium separation \(h\) in terms of \(m,R,Q,\omega ,g\) and the fundamental constants \(\varepsilon_{0},\mu_{0}\).

---

### Step 1‚ÄÉElectrostatic force between the sphere and its image charge  
Principles / Original Formulas / Assumptions  
\[\boxed{F=\frac{1}{4\pi\varepsilon_{0}}\frac{|q_{1}q_{2}|}{r^{2}}}\]  

Derivation  
Treating the uniformly charged sphere as a point charge \(Q\) at its centre (valid outside the sphere) and its image as \(-Q\) at the mirror point, the separation of the pair is \(r=2h\).  The force magnitude is  
\[
\begin{align}
F_{\mathrm e}
      &=\frac{1}{4\pi\varepsilon_{0}}
        \frac{Q^{2}}{(2h)^{2}}
        =\frac{Q^{2}}{16\pi\varepsilon_{0}h^{2}},\tag{1}\label{Fe}\\
\end{align}
\]
directed \emph{downward} (attractive).

---

### Step 2‚ÄÉMagnetic moment of the uniformly charged rotating sphere  
Principles / Original Formulas / Assumptions  
\[\boxed{\mathbf J=\rho\,(\boldsymbol\omega\times\mathbf r)},\qquad
       \rho=\frac{Q}{\dfrac{4}{3}\pi R^{3}}\]  
\[\boxed{\boldsymbol\mu=\frac12\int\mathbf r\times\mathbf J\,\mathrm dV}\]

Derivation  
\[
\begin{align}
\mu
   &=\frac12 \rho\,\omega \int r_{\perp}^{2}\,\mathrm dV
     =\frac12 \rho\,\omega\!\left(\frac{8\pi R^{5}}{15}\right) \nonumber\\
   &=\frac{Q}{\tfrac43\pi R^{3}}\,
      \frac{\omega}{2}\,
      \frac{8\pi R^{5}}{15}
     =\frac15\,Q\omega R^{2},\tag{2}\label{mu}
\end{align}
\]
so \(\boldsymbol\mu=\mu\,\hat{\mathbf z}\).

---

### Step 3‚ÄÉMagnetic interaction with the superconducting plate  
Principles / Original Formulas / Assumptions  
\[\boxed{\text{Meissner boundary: }B_{\perp}=0\ \Longrightarrow\ 
          \boldsymbol\mu_{\text{im}}=-\boldsymbol\mu}\]  
\[\boxed{U=\frac{\mu_{0}}{4\pi r^{3}}
        \Bigl[\boldsymbol\mu_{1}\!\cdot\!\boldsymbol\mu_{2}
              -3(\boldsymbol\mu_{1}\!\cdot\!\hat{\mathbf r})
               (\boldsymbol\mu_{2}\!\cdot\!\hat{\mathbf r})\Bigr]}\]  
\[\boxed{F_{\mathrm m}=-\frac{\mathrm dU}{\mathrm dh}}\]

Derivation  
With \(\boldsymbol\mu_{1}=\boldsymbol\mu,\ \boldsymbol\mu_{2}=-\boldsymbol\mu\) and centre-to-centre vector \(\mathbf r=2h\,\hat{\mathbf z}\):

\[
\begin{align}
U&=\frac{\mu_{0}}{4\pi(2h)^{3}}
    \left[-\mu^{2}-3(\mu)(-\mu)\right]
   =\frac{\mu_{0}\mu^{2}}{16\pi h^{3}},\tag{3}\label{U}\\[4pt]
F_{\mathrm m}
  &=-\frac{\mathrm dU}{\mathrm dh}
   =\frac{3\mu_{0}\mu^{2}}{16\pi h^{4}}\nonumber\\
  &=\frac{3\mu_{0}Q^{2}\omega^{2}R^{4}}{400\pi h^{4}},\tag{4}\label{Fm}
\end{align}
\]
directed \emph{upward} (repulsive).

---

### Step 4‚ÄÉForce balance and determination of \(h\)  
Principles / Original Formulas / Assumptions  
\[\boxed{F_{\mathrm m}-F_{\mathrm e}-mg=0}\]

Derivation  
Insert \eqref{Fe} and \eqref{Fm}:

\[
\begin{align}
\frac{3\mu_{0}Q^{2}\omega^{2}R^{4}}{400\pi h^{4}}
      &=\frac{Q^{2}}{16\pi\varepsilon_{0}h^{2}}+mg.\tag{5}
\end{align}
\]

Let \(y=h^{2}\;(>0)\).  Multiplying by \(h^{4}=y^{2}\) gives the quadratic

\[
\begin{align}
mg\,y^{2}
+\frac{Q^{2}}{16\pi\varepsilon_{0}}\,y
-\frac{3\mu_{0}Q^{2}\omega^{2}R^{4}}{400\pi}=0.\tag{6}\label{quad}
\end{align}
\]

Using the quadratic-formula and selecting the physically admissible (\(y>0\)) root:

\[
\begin{align}
y&=
\frac{-\dfrac{Q^{2}}{16\pi\varepsilon_{0}}
      +\sqrt{\left(\dfrac{Q^{2}}{16\pi\varepsilon_{0}}\right)^{2}
              +\dfrac{3\mu_{0}mgQ^{2}\omega^{2}R^{4}}{100\pi}}}
     {2mg}.\tag{7}
\end{align}
\]

Finally \(h=\sqrt{y}\):

\[
\begin{align}
h=
\sqrt{
     \frac{-\dfrac{Q^{2}}{16\pi\varepsilon_{0}}
           +\sqrt{\dfrac{Q^{4}}{256\pi^{2}\varepsilon_{0}^{2}}
                  +\dfrac{3\mu_{0}mgQ^{2}\omega^{2}R^{4}}{100\pi}}}
          {2mg}
     }.\tag{8}\label{h}
\end{align}
\]

---

### Final Answer
\[
\begin{align}
\boxed{%
h=
\sqrt{
     \frac{-\dfrac{Q^{2}}{16\pi\varepsilon_{0}}
           +\sqrt{\dfrac{Q^{4}}{256\pi^{2}\varepsilon_{0}^{2}}
                  +\dfrac{3\mu_{0} m g Q^{2}\omega^{2} R^{4}}{100\pi}}}
          {2 m g}
     }}
\end{align}
\]

This is the equilibrium distance between the centre of the uniformly charged, rotating sphere and the superconducting plate, obtained by balancing magnetic repulsion against electrostatic attraction and weight.

# Refined Solution
### Problem Statement Explanation
We have a perfectly plane, loss-less three‚Äìlayer system arranged symmetrically as  
‚ÄÉmedium 2  (high refractive index ${n_2}$)  
‚ÄÉ‚ÄÉ‚Üí thin film 1 (low refractive index ${n_1}$, physical thickness $d$)  
‚ÄÉ‚ÄÉ‚Üí medium 2 (same index ${n_2}$ as the incident side).

For compactness we introduce the dimensionless index ratio  
‚ÄÉ$n\equiv\dfrac{n_1}{n_2}<1$.

A monochromatic, s-polarised plane wave of vacuum angular frequency $\omega$ and
wavelength **inside medium 2**

‚ÄÉ$\displaystyle \lambda=\frac{2\pi c}{\omega\,n_2}$

impinges on the first ($2\,\to\,1$) interface at an external incidence angle $i_2$ (measured from the surface normal).
Because $n_1<n_2$, angles satisfying

‚ÄÉ$\sin i_2 > n = \dfrac{n_1}{n_2}$

are above the critical angle; consequently the field in the film is evanescent and each single interface on its own would exhibit total internal reflection (TIR).
The finite film nevertheless allows *frustrated* TIR, i.e. coherent coupling to the second interface, so that multiple reflections of Fabry‚ÄìP√©rot type occur.

The task is to find the *total s-polarised intensity reflectance*

‚ÄÉ$\displaystyle R_s \equiv |r_{\text{tot}}|^{\,2}$

in terms of the four independent parameters $\lambda,\,d,\,i_2$, and $n$.
The media are assumed non-absorbing; interference is therefore perfectly coherent.


### Step 1
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions  
\[\boxed{n_2\sin i_2 = n_1\sin i_1}\]  
\[\boxed{\sin i_2 > n \Longrightarrow \text{TIR and evanescent field in layer}}\]

Derivation  
\[
\begin{align}
n_2\sin i_2 &= n_1\sin i_1 \label{SnellLaw}\tag{1}\\[4pt]
\sin i_1 &= \frac{n_2}{n_1}\sin i_2
          = \frac{\sin i_2}{n}. \nonumber
\end{align}
\]
Because $\sin i_2>n$, we have $\sin i_1>1$; hence $i_1$ is complex and the field inside the film decays exponentially rather than propagating.


### Step 2
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions  
\[\boxed{r^{(s)}_{ab}=\dfrac{n_a\cos i_a-n_b\cos i_b}{n_a\cos i_a+n_b\cos i_b}}\]  
\[\boxed{t^{(s)}_{ab}=\dfrac{2n_a\cos i_a}{n_a\cos i_a+n_b\cos i_b}}\]

Derivation  
For the first interface (medium 2 ‚Üí medium 1):
\[
\begin{align}
r_{21} &= \frac{n_2\cos i_2-n_1\cos i_1}{n_2\cos i_2+n_1\cos i_1},\nonumber\\
t_{21} &= \frac{2n_2\cos i_2}{n_2\cos i_2+n_1\cos i_1}. \label{r21t21}\tag{2}
\end{align}
\]
Interchanging the media flips only the numerator‚Äôs sign, therefore  
$r_{12}=-\,r_{21}$.


### Step 3
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions  
\[\boxed{k_2=\dfrac{2\pi}{\lambda}},\qquad
\boxed{k_1 = n\,k_2 = \dfrac{2\pi n}{\lambda}}\]  
\[\boxed{\delta=k_1 d\cos i_1}\]  
\[\boxed{r_{\text{tot}}=\dfrac{r_{21}+r_{12}e^{2i\delta}}{1+r_{21}r_{12}e^{2i\delta}}}\]

Derivation  
The single-pass *phase thickness* of the film is
\[
\begin{align}
\delta &= k_1 d \cos i_1
       = \frac{2\pi d}{\lambda}\,n\cos i_1. \label{delta}\tag{3}
\end{align}
\]
The total amplitude reflection coefficient of a three-layer stack with coherent multiple reflections is the standard Fabry‚ÄìP√©rot expression given in the last boxed formula.


### Step 4
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions  
\[\boxed{r_{12}=-\,r_{21}\equiv -\,r}\]

Derivation  
Substituting $r_{12}=-r$ into the Fabry‚ÄìP√©rot formula,
\[
\begin{align}
r_{\text{tot}}
  &=\frac{r-r\,e^{2i\delta}}{1-r^{2}e^{2i\delta}}
   = r\,\frac{1-e^{2i\delta}}{1-r^{2}e^{2i\delta}}. \label{rtotPrelim}\tag{4}
\end{align}
\]


### Step 5
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions  
\[\boxed{\cos i_1 = i\kappa,\quad
        \kappa=\sqrt{\sin^{2} i_1-1}}\]  
\[\boxed{\alpha =\sqrt{\sin^{2} i_2-n^{2}}}\]

Derivation  
Because $i_1$ is complex we write $\cos i_1=i\kappa$ with real positive $\kappa$.  
Using (\ref{SnellLaw}) and $\sin^{2}i_1-1=\dfrac{\sin^{2}i_2}{n^{2}}-1$ gives
\[
\begin{align}
\kappa &=\frac{\sqrt{\sin^{2} i_2-n^{2}}}{n}
       \equiv\frac{\alpha}{n}. \nonumber
\end{align}
\]
Insert $\cos i_1=i\kappa$ into (\ref{r21t21}):

\[
\begin{align}
r \equiv r_{21}
      &=\frac{n_2\cos i_2-n_1(i\kappa)}
             {n_2\cos i_2+n_1(i\kappa)}
      =\frac{\cos i_2-i\alpha}
             {\cos i_2+i\alpha}. \label{rSingle}\tag{5}
\end{align}
\]

Magnitude $\lvert r\rvert=1$ (as expected for TIR).  Therefore $r=e^{i\theta}$ with  

\[
\begin{align}
\sin\theta
    &= -\frac{2\alpha\cos i_2}{1-n^{2}}. \label{sinTheta}\tag{6}
\end{align}
\]


### Step 6
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions  
\[\boxed{\delta=i\beta,\quad\beta=\dfrac{2\pi d}{\lambda}\,\alpha}\]  
\[\boxed{e^{2i\delta}=e^{-2\beta}\equiv s,\quad 0<s<1}\]

Derivation  
With $\cos i_1=i\kappa=i\alpha/n$ in (\ref{delta}):
\[
\begin{align}
\delta &=\frac{2\pi d}{\lambda}\,n(i\kappa)
       =i\frac{2\pi d}{\lambda}\alpha
       \equiv i\beta. \label{beta}\tag{7}
\end{align}
\]
Hence the round-trip factor is purely real and attenuating:
$e^{2i\delta}=e^{-2\beta}=s$.


### Step 7
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions  
\[\boxed{R_s=|\,r_{\text{tot}}|^{\,2}}\]

Derivation  
Insert $r=e^{i\theta}$ (\ref{rSingle}), $s=e^{-2\beta}$ (\ref{beta}) into (\ref{rtotPrelim}):

\[
\begin{align}
r_{\text{tot}}
      &=e^{i\theta}\frac{1-s}{1-se^{2i\theta}}, \nonumber\\[6pt]
|r_{\text{tot}}|^{2}
      &=\frac{(1-s)^{2}}{(1-s)^{2}+4s\sin^{2}\theta}. \label{RsBase}\tag{8}
\end{align}
\]

Because $s=e^{-2\beta}$ and $\sin\theta$ comes from (\ref{sinTheta}), we obtain

\[
\begin{align}
R_s
 &=\left[
     1+\left(
         \frac{2\,e^{-\beta}}{1-e^{-2\beta}}
         \cdot
         \frac{2\alpha\cos i_2}{1-n^{2}}
       \right)^{2}
   \right]^{-1},
 \qquad
 \beta=\frac{2\pi d}{\lambda}\alpha. \label{RsAlmost}\tag{9}
\end{align}
\]

Finally substituting $\alpha=\sqrt{\sin^{2}i_2-n^{2}}$ and
$\cos i_2=\sqrt{1-\sin^{2}i_2}$ gives

\[
\begin{align}
R_s
 &=\Bigg[
     1+\Bigg(
        \frac{2\,e^{-\tfrac{2\pi d}{\lambda}
                       \sqrt{\sin^{2} i_2-n^{2}}}}
             {1-e^{-\tfrac{4\pi d}{\lambda}
                       \sqrt{\sin^{2} i_2-n^{2}}}}
        \cdot
        \frac{2\sqrt{\,\bigl(1-\sin^{2} i_2\bigr)
                         \bigl(\sin^{2} i_2-n^{2}\bigr)}}
             {1-n^{2}}
       \Bigg)^{2}
   \Bigg]^{-1}. \label{RsFinal}\tag{10}
\end{align}
\]


### Final Answer
\[
\begin{align}
\boxed{%
R_s=
\left[
1+
\left(
      \frac{2\,
            e^{-\dfrac{2\pi d}{\lambda}
                     \sqrt{\sin^{2} i_2-n^{2}}}}
           {1-
            e^{-\dfrac{4\pi d}{\lambda}
                     \sqrt{\sin^{2} i_2-n^{2}}}}
      \;\cdot\;
      \frac{2\sqrt{\bigl(1-\sin^{2} i_2\bigr)
                    \bigl(\sin^{2} i_2-n^{2}\bigr)}}
           {\,1-n^{2}}
\right)^{2}
\right]^{-1}}
\end{align}
\]

The formula delivers the total s-polarised intensity reflectance of a low-index film ($n<1$) of physical thickness $d$, sandwiched between two identical higher-index media $n_2$, for any incidence angle $i_2$ above the critical angle ($\sin i_2>n$).

# Refined Solution
### Problem Statement Explanation  
We analyse a speed‚Äìgoverning device that rotates about a fixed vertical axis through point O.  

Given parts and data  
1. Point O initially carries a positive point charge \(+Q\).  
2. A light, smooth, straight, insulating tube is rigidly attached to the axis; it lies in the horizontal plane, so the radial coordinate of anything inside the tube is the distance \(r\) from O.  
3. Inside the tube a photo-switch \(A\) is located at the radius  
   \(OA = L\).  
4. A light, ideal (Hookean) spring of free (natural) length \(L/4\) is fixed to O; its outer end is connected to a small insulating ball of  
   ‚Ä¢ mass \(m\)  
   ‚Ä¢ positive charge \(q\).  
   The ball can slide only along the tube.  
5. An external driving torque gradually increases the tube‚Äôs angular speed \(\omega\).  
   ‚Ä¢ When the ball just reaches \(A\)(\(r=L\)) in steady circular motion, the switch acts:   
     a) the driving torque is removed (zero afterwards);  
     b) the charge at O flips instantaneously from \(+Q\) to \(-Q\).  

6. After the charge sign reversal the ball moves to a new steady position \(B\), experimentally found to be at  
   \(OB = L/2\).  

Task  
Determine the tube‚Äôs angular speed \(\omega\) when the ball is at \(B\) (call it \(\omega_B\)) in terms of \(Q,\;q,\;m,\;L\) and Coulomb‚Äôs constant \(k\).

Basic assumptions  
‚Ä¢ The tube and spring are mass-less; their moments of inertia are negligible.  
‚Ä¢ The tube is perfectly smooth, so the only forces on the ball are radial (spring and electrostatic).  
‚Ä¢ After the driving torque is switched off no external torque acts on the ball about the axis, hence its axial angular momentum is conserved.  
‚Ä¢ Gravity acts vertically and therefore exerts no torque about the vertical axis.

Symbols  
\(r\) : instantaneous radius of the ball.  
\(K\) : spring (Hooke) constant (not given, will be solved for).  
\(\omega_A\): angular speed immediately before the charge flips (ball at \(A\)).  
\(\omega_B\): sought angular speed when the ball is at \(B\;(r=L/2)\).

---

### Step 1‚ÄÉRadial equilibrium at \(A\;(r=L)\) while charge at O is \(+Q\)
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions  
\[\boxed{F_{\text{spring}} = K\,(r-L/4)}\]  
\[\boxed{F_{\text{Coulomb}} = \dfrac{k\,q\,Q}{r^{2}}}\]  
\[\boxed{\sum F_{\text{in}}-\sum F_{\text{out}} = m\,r\,\omega^{2}}\]

Derivation  
For \(r=L\) the spring pulls inward, the like charges repel outward:
\[
\begin{align}
K\!\left(L-\frac{L}{4}\right)-\frac{k\,q\,Q}{L^{2}}
   &=m\,L\,\omega_A^{2}
   \label{A_eq}\tag{1}
\end{align}
\]

---

### Step 2‚ÄÉRadial equilibrium at \(B\;(r=L/2)\) after the charge has become \(-Q\)
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions  
\[\boxed{F_{\text{spring}} = K\,(r-L/4)}\]  
\[\boxed{F_{\text{Coulomb}} = \dfrac{k\,q\,Q}{r^{2}}\quad(\text{attractive,\,inward})}\]  
\[\boxed{\sum F_{\text{in}}-\sum F_{\text{out}} = m\,r\,\omega^{2}}\]

Derivation  
Both forces are inward:
\[
\begin{align}
K\!\left(\frac{L}{2}-\frac{L}{4}\right)+
\frac{k\,q\,Q}{\left(\tfrac{L}{2}\right)^{2}}
   &=m\!\left(\tfrac{L}{2}\right)\omega_B^{2}\notag\\
K\frac{L}{4}+\frac{4kqQ}{L^{2}}
   &=\frac{mL}{2}\,\omega_B^{2}
   \label{B_eq}\tag{2}
\end{align}
\]

---

### Step 3‚ÄÉAngular-momentum conservation from \(A\) to \(B\)
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions  
\[\boxed{L_z = m\,r^{2}\omega=\text{constant}}\]

Derivation  
\[
\begin{align}
mL^{2}\omega_A
      &=m\!\left(\frac{L}{2}\right)^{2}\omega_B\notag\\
\omega_B&=4\,\omega_A
\label{omega_rel}\tag{3}
\end{align}
\]

---

### Step 4‚ÄÉEliminate \(K\) and \(\omega_A\); solve for \(\omega_B\)
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions  
\[
\boxed{\text{Use Eqs.\;(\ref{A_eq}),\;(\ref{B_eq}),\;(\ref{omega_rel})}}
\]

Derivation  

1.  From (1):
\[
\begin{align}
mL\omega_A^{2}=K\frac{3L}{4}-\frac{kqQ}{L^{2}}
\label{mLwA2}\tag{4}
\end{align}
\]

2.  Insert \(\omega_B=4\omega_A\) into (2):
\[
\begin{align}
K\frac{L}{4}+\frac{4kqQ}{L^{2}}
   &=\frac{mL}{2}\,(4\omega_A)^{2}
   =8\,mL\omega_A^{2}
\label{Subs}\tag{5}
\end{align}
\]

3.  Replace \(mL\omega_A^{2}\) in (5) by (4) and solve for \(K\):
\[
\begin{align}
K\frac{L}{4}+\frac{4kqQ}{L^{2}}
&=8\!\left(K\frac{3L}{4}-\frac{kqQ}{L^{2}}\right)\notag\\
\frac{L}{4}K+\frac{4kqQ}{L^{2}}
&=6LK-\frac{8kqQ}{L^{2}}\notag\\
\frac{23L}{4}K&=\frac{12kqQ}{L^{2}}\notag\\
K&=\frac{48\,k\,q\,Q}{23\,L^{3}}
\label{K_result}\tag{6}
\end{align}
\]

4.  Substitute this \(K\) back into (2) to find \(\omega_B\):
\[
\begin{align}
\frac{mL}{2}\omega_B^{2}
&=K\frac{L}{4}+\frac{4kqQ}{L^{2}}\notag\\
&=\frac{48kqQ}{23L^{3}}\cdot\frac{L}{4}
  +\frac{4kqQ}{L^{2}}\notag\\
&=\frac{12kqQ}{23L^{2}}+\frac{4kqQ}{L^{2}}
  =\frac{104kqQ}{23L^{2}}
\notag\\[6pt]
\therefore\;
\omega_B^{2}
&=\frac{2}{mL}\cdot\frac{104kqQ}{23L^{2}}
 =\frac{208}{23}\,\frac{kqQ}{mL^{3}}
\label{omegaB2}\tag{7}
\end{align}
\]

Taking the square root:
\[
\omega_B
   =\sqrt{\frac{208}{23}}\,
     \sqrt{\frac{kqQ}{mL^{3}}}
   =4\,\sqrt{\frac{13\,k\,q\,Q}{23\,m\,L^{3}}}.
\]

---

### Final Answer
\[
\begin{align}
\boxed{\displaystyle
\omega_B = 4\,\sqrt{\frac{13\,k\,q\,Q}{23\,m\,L^{3}}}}
\end{align}
\]

# Refined Solution
### Problem Statement Explanation  
We consider  
‚Ä¢ Two identical relativistic particles X (rest mass M each) that interact, in their centre-of-momentum (zero-momentum) frame C, through an attractive central force  

‚ÄÉ‚ÄÉF(r)=Œ±/r¬≤‚ÄÉ‚ÄÉ(Œ±>0).  

Because F(r)=‚àídV/dr, the potential energy is  

‚ÄÉ‚ÄÉV(r)=‚àíŒ±/r.  

Treating the bound pair semiclassically (Bohr‚ÄìSommerfeld quantisation) we label the stationary levels by a principal quantum number n=1,2,‚Ä¶.  
The tasks are  

1. Determine the largest coupling constant Œ±_c for which the ground state (n=1) is physically admissible, i.e. the orbital speed remains strictly smaller than the speed of light c.  

2. Fix the coupling at one half of that critical value, Œ± = Œ±_c/2.  
   In the laboratory frame L, an X‚ÇÇ molecule in its ground state (n=1) and at rest is hit by an ultra-relativistic, effectively mass-less projectile whose energy we call Œµ.  
   The impact excites the molecule to the first excited state (n=2) and a single photon is emitted,  

‚ÄÉ‚ÄÉprojectile (Œµ) + X‚ÇÇ(1) ‚Üí X‚ÇÇ(2) + Œ≥.  

   We have to find the minimum projectile energy Œµ_min that makes this reaction kinematically possible.  

Assumptions used throughout  
‚Ä¢ Bohr‚ÄìSommerfeld angular-momentum quantisation L=n‚Ñè.  
‚Ä¢ Each particle moves in a circular orbit of radius r/2 around the centre of mass (the separation between the particles is r).  
‚Ä¢ Special-relativistic kinematics is employed exactly (Œ≥=1/‚àö{1‚àív¬≤/c¬≤}).  
‚Ä¢ For uniform circular motion the required centripetal force equals Œ≥Mv¬≤/R.  
‚Ä¢ The projectile is mass-less; hence its energy and momentum obey Œµ = Pc.  
‚Ä¢ At threshold the Mandelstam invariant s = (p‚ÇÅ+p‚ÇÇ)¬≤ takes its minimal value; this is the standard way to impose energy‚Äìmomentum conservation at threshold.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------

### Step 1 ‚Äî Bohr‚ÄìSommerfeld Quantisation  

Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions  
\[\boxed{L = n\hbar}\]  
\[\boxed{p = \gamma M v}\]

\[
\begin{align}
L_{\text{tot}}
      &= 2\!\left(p\;\frac{r}{2}\right)
       = p\,r
       = \gamma M v r
       = n\hbar ,                                                  \label{eq:L_quant}\tag{1}\\[6pt]
\Longrightarrow\quad
r &=\frac{n\hbar}{\gamma M v}.                                     \label{eq:r_of_v}\tag{1a}
\end{align}
\]

----------------------------------------------------------------------------

### Step 2 ‚Äî Force Balance (Uniform Circular Motion)  

Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions  
\[\boxed{F(r)=\dfrac{\alpha}{r^{2}}}\]  
\[\boxed{F_{\text{centr}}=\dfrac{\gamma M v^{2}}{R}}\]

For either particle the orbit radius is R = r/2. Equating magnitudes,

\[
\begin{align}
\frac{\alpha}{r^{2}}
      &= \frac{\gamma M v^{2}}{r/2}
       = \frac{2\gamma M v^{2}}{r},                                \label{eq:ForceBalance}\tag{2}\\[4pt]
\Longrightarrow\quad
\alpha &= 2\gamma M v^{2} r.                                       \label{eq:alpha_prelim}\tag{2a}
\end{align}
\]

----------------------------------------------------------------------------

### Step 3 ‚Äî Eliminating r and Œ≥  

(Combine Eqs. \eqref{eq:L_quant} and \eqref{eq:alpha_prelim}. No additional principle is introduced.)

\[
\begin{align}
\alpha &= 2\gamma M v^{2}\left(\frac{n\hbar}{\gamma M v}\right)
       = 2n\hbar v.                                                \label{eq:alpha_v}\tag{3}
\end{align}
\]

Remark: the Lorentz factor Œ≥ and the mass M cancel; the coupling is proportional to the orbital speed v.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------

### Step 4 ‚Äî Critical Coupling Œ±_c  

Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions  
\[\boxed{v < c}\]

The maximal admissible coupling corresponds to the limiting case v‚Üíc‚Åª.  
For the ground state n=1,

\[
\begin{align}
\alpha_{c} = 2\hbar c.                                             \label{eq:alpha_c}\tag{4}
\end{align}
\]

----------------------------------------------------------------------------

### Step 5 ‚Äî Orbital Speed and Lorentz Factor for Œ± = Œ±_c/2  

From now on we set  

\[
\alpha = \frac{\alpha_{c}}{2} = \hbar c.                          \label{eq:alpha_fixed}\tag{5a}
\]

Principle already established (Eq. \eqref{eq:alpha_v}):  
\[\boxed{v = \dfrac{\alpha}{2n\hbar}}\]

\[
\begin{align}
v_{n}      &= \frac{\alpha}{2n\hbar} = \frac{c}{2n},               \label{eq:v_n}\tag{5}\\[6pt]
\gamma_{n} &= \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-v_{n}^{2}/c^{2}}}
           = \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-\dfrac{1}{4n^{2}}}}
           = \frac{2n}{\sqrt{4n^{2}-1}}.                           \label{eq:gamma_n}\tag{5b}
\end{align}
\]
(In particular Œ≥‚ÇÅ = 2/‚àö3 and Œ≥‚ÇÇ = 4/‚àö15.)

----------------------------------------------------------------------------

### Step 6 ‚Äî Internal (Rest) Energies of X‚ÇÇ  

Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions  
\[\boxed{E_{\text{X‚ÇÇ}} = 2\gamma M c^{2} + V(r)}\]  
\[\boxed{V(r) = -\dfrac{\alpha}{r}}\]  
\[\boxed{r_{n} = \dfrac{n\hbar}{\gamma_{n} M v_{n}}}\]

\[
\begin{align}
\frac{\alpha}{r_{n}}
        &= \alpha \frac{\gamma_{n} M v_{n}}{n\hbar}
         = (\hbar c)\frac{\gamma_{n} M (c/2n)}{n\hbar}
         = \frac{\gamma_{n} M c^{2}}{2n^{2}},                     \label{eq:alpha_r}\tag{6a}\\[6pt]
E_{n} &= 2\gamma_{n} M c^{2} - \frac{\alpha}{r_{n}}
      = 2\gamma_{n} M c^{2} - \frac{\gamma_{n} M c^{2}}{2n^{2}}
      = \gamma_{n} M c^{2}\!\left(2 - \frac{1}{2n^{2}}\right).    \label{eq:E_n}\tag{6b}
\end{align}
\]

Explicitly  

\[
\begin{align}
E_{1} &= \sqrt{3}\,M c^{2}, \qquad
E_{2} = \frac{\sqrt{15}}{2}\,M c^{2}.                             \label{eq:E_levels}\tag{6c}
\end{align}
\]

----------------------------------------------------------------------------

### Step 7 ‚Äî Threshold Condition for the Projectile Energy  

Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions  
\[\boxed{s = (p_{1}+p_{2})^{2}\quad\text{(Lorentz invariant)}}\]  
\[\boxed{\varepsilon = P c}\quad\text{(mass-less projectile)}\]

Initial four-momenta in the laboratory frame L  
\[
p_{\text{proj}} = \bigl(\varepsilon/c,\; \varepsilon/c\bigr),\qquad
p_{\text{X‚ÇÇ(1)}} = \bigl(E_{1}/c,\; 0\bigr).
\]

Hence  
\[
\begin{align}
s_{\text{init}}
     &= (E_{1}+\varepsilon)^{2} - (\varepsilon)^{2}
      = E_{1}^{2} + 2\,\varepsilon\,E_{1}.                        \label{eq:s_init}\tag{7}
\end{align}
\]

Final state at threshold: excited molecule at rest plus a photon whose energy‚Äîand therefore four-product with the molecule‚Äîtends to zero. Consequently

\[
s_{\text{final,min}} = E_{2}^{2}.
\]

Energy‚Äìmomentum conservation at threshold demands \(s_{\text{init}} = s_{\text{final,min}}\):

\[
\begin{align}
E_{1}^{2} + 2\,\varepsilon\,E_{1} = E_{2}^{2}.                    \label{eq:threshold}\tag{7a}
\end{align}
\]

----------------------------------------------------------------------------

### Step 8 ‚Äî Minimum Projectile Energy \(\varepsilon_{\text{min}}\)

\[
\begin{align}
\varepsilon_{\text{min}}
   &= \frac{E_{2}^{2} - E_{1}^{2}}{2E_{1}}
    = \frac{\bigl(\tfrac{\sqrt{15}}{2}M c^{2}\bigr)^{2}
            - \bigl(\sqrt{3}\,M c^{2}\bigr)^{2}}
           {2\sqrt{3}\,M c^{2}}                                    \tag{8}\\[6pt]
   &= \frac{\bigl(\tfrac{15}{4} - 3\bigr) M^{2}c^{4}}
           {2\sqrt{3}\,M c^{2}}
    = \frac{3}{8\sqrt{3}}\,M c^{2}
    = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{8}\,M c^{2}.                                 \label{eq:Eproj}\tag{8a}
\end{align}
\]

----------------------------------------------------------------------------

### Final Answer  
\[
\begin{align}
\boxed{\;\varepsilon_{\text{min}} = \dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{8}\,M c^{2}\;}
\end{align}
\]

# Refined Solution
### Problem Statement Explanation
A thin, plane‚Äìparallel film of constant geometric thickness  
‚ÄÉd (0 ‚â§ y ‚â§ d)  
is filled with a non-dispersive graded‚Äìindex material whose refractive index varies linearly with the height y measured from the lower interface (y = 0):

‚ÄÉn(y)=n_a+k\,y ,‚ÄÉk‚â°(n_b-n_a)/d ,‚ÄÉn_b>n_a>0.  

Monochromatic light of vacuum wavelength Œª propagates in air (refractive index n‚ÇÄ = 1) and strikes the lower interface under an external angle of incidence i (measured from the surface normal, +y).  
Inside the film the ray bends continuously, reaches the upper interface, is reflected once (reflection introduces no phase change), returns to the lower interface and leaves the film.

Two neighbouring incident rays hit the lower interface at points separated by the distance 2S along +x.  
For the first ray the entry point is Q (taken as x = 0), the exit point after the single reflection is P, and OP = 2S.  
Required: the phase difference œÜ between the two emerging rays, expressed only in the given quantities (d, n_a, n_b, i, Œª); the auxiliary  S must disappear.

Assumptions  
1. Geometrical‚Äìoptics approximation (Œª ‚â™ characteristic lengths).  
2. The refractive-index gradient is non-dispersive at Œª.  
3. Reflection causes no phase reversal.  
4. The interference is observed in air after both rays have left the film, so the relevant quantity is the total optical-path difference up to the common observation plane.

---

### Step 1 &ensp;Snell-type Invariant in a 1-D Gradient Medium
\[
\boxed{n(y)\,\sin\theta(y)=\text{constant}}
\]

\[
\begin{align}
&\text{(external incidence in air: constant}=n_0\sin i=\sin i)\nonumber\\
\Rightarrow\quad
\sin\theta(y)&=\frac{\sin i}{n(y)},\label{eq:sin}\tag{1}\\
\cos\theta(y)&=\sqrt{1-\sin^2\theta(y)}
             =\frac{\sqrt{n^{2}(y)-\sin^{2} i}}{n(y)}.\label{eq:cos}\tag{2}
\end{align}
\]

---

### Step 2 &ensp;Horizontal Shift of One Up-and-Down Ray Path
\[
\boxed{\mathrm dx=\tan\theta(y)\,\mathrm dy}
\]
\[
\boxed{\tan\theta(y)=\frac{\sin\theta(y)}{\cos\theta(y)}
                   =\frac{\sin i}{\sqrt{\,n^{2}(y)-\sin^{2} i\,}}}
\]

\[
\begin{align}
2S &= 2\int_{0}^{d}\tan\theta(y)\,\mathrm dy \nonumber \\
   &= 2\sin i\int_{0}^{d} \frac{\mathrm dy}{\sqrt{\,n^{2}(y)-\sin^{2} i\,}} \nonumber\\
   &\xrightarrow{u=n(y),\;\mathrm dy =\frac{d}{n_b-n_a}\,\mathrm du}
     \frac{2d\sin i}{\,n_b-n_a}
     \int_{n_a}^{n_b}\frac{\mathrm du}{\sqrt{u^{2}-\sin^{2} i}}\nonumber\\
   &=\frac{2d\sin i}{\,n_b-n_a}\,
     \ln\!\left(
           \frac{n_b+\sqrt{n_b^{2}-\sin^{2} i}}
                {n_a+\sqrt{n_a^{2}-\sin^{2} i}}
         \right).\label{eq:2S}\tag{3}
\end{align}
\]

---

### Step 3 &ensp;Optical Length Inside the Film
\[
\boxed{\mathrm d\ell_{\text{opt}} = n(y)\,\mathrm ds}\qquad
\boxed{\mathrm ds=\frac{\mathrm dy}{\cos\theta(y)}}
\]

\[
\begin{align}
L &= 2\int_{0}^{d} \frac{n^{2}(y)\,\mathrm dy}
                         {\sqrt{\,n^{2}(y)-\sin^{2} i\,}}.\label{eq:L}\tag{4}
\end{align}
\]

Because the integrand depends only on y (not on the different x-positions of various rays), every ray that performs the single reflection acquires the same internal optical length. Hence
\[
\boxed{\Delta L_{\text{inside}} = 0.}\label{eq:zero}\tag{5}
\]

---

### Step 4 &ensp;Optical-Path Difference Accumulated in Air
\[
\boxed{\Delta\ell_{\text{air}} = n_0\,\sin i\,\Delta x
      \quad (n_0=1)}
\]

\[
\begin{align}
\Delta L_{\text{air}} &= \sin i\,(2S) \nonumber\\
                      &= \sin i\,
                         \frac{2d\sin i}{\,n_b-n_a}
                         \ln\!\left(
                               \frac{n_b+\sqrt{n_b^{2}-\sin^{2} i}}
                                    {n_a+\sqrt{n_a^{2}-\sin^{2} i}}
                             \right)\nonumber\\
                      &= \frac{2d\sin^{2} i}{\,n_b-n_a}\,
                         \ln\!\left(
                               \frac{n_b+\sqrt{\,n_b^{2}-\sin^{2} i\,}}
                                    {n_a+\sqrt{\,n_a^{2}-\sin^{2} i\,}}
                             \right).\label{eq:DLair}\tag{6}
\end{align}
\]

Since the internal contribution is zero (eq. \eqref{eq:zero}),
\[
\Delta L = \Delta L_{\text{air}}.\label{eq:DL}\tag{7}
\]

---

### Step 5 &ensp;Phase Difference Between the Two Emerging Rays
\[
\boxed{\varphi = \dfrac{2\pi}{\lambda}\,\Delta L}
\]

\[
\begin{align}
\varphi &= \frac{2\pi}{\lambda}\,
          \frac{2d\sin^{2} i}{\,n_b-n_a}\,
          \ln\!\left(
                \frac{n_b+\sqrt{\,n_b^{2}-\sin^{2} i\,}}
                     {n_a+\sqrt{\,n_a^{2}-\sin^{2} i\,}}
              \right)\nonumber\\
        &= \frac{4\pi d\,\sin^{2} i}{\lambda\,(n_b-n_a)}
           \ln\!\left(
                 \frac{n_b+\sqrt{\,n_b^{2}-\sin^{2} i\,}}
                      {n_a+\sqrt{\,n_a^{2}-\sin^{2} i\,}}
               \right).\label{eq:phi}\tag{8}
\end{align}
\]

---

### Final Answer
\[
\begin{align}
\boxed{%
\displaystyle
\varphi = \frac{4\pi d\,\sin^{2} i}{\lambda\,(n_b-n_a)}
           \;\ln\!\left(
                     \frac{n_b+\sqrt{\,n_b^{2}-\sin^{2} i\,}}
                          {n_a+\sqrt{\,n_a^{2}-\sin^{2} i\,}}
                 \right)}
\end{align}
\]

The result depends only on the given parameters (d, n_a, n_b, i, Œª) and contains no reference to the auxiliary distance S, satisfying the requirements of the problem.

# Refined Solution
### Problem Statement Explanation
We analyse the planar motion of a compound pendulum made of  
1. a light, inextensible string OB of fixed length $l_{1}$, and  
2. an attached uniform thin rod AB of mass $m$ and length $l_{2}$.

Reference frame (inertial)  
‚Ä¢ Origin at the fixed suspension point $O$.  
‚Ä¢ $x$-axis: horizontal, positive to the right ($\mathbf i$).  
‚Ä¢ $y$-axis: vertical, positive upward ($\mathbf j$).  
‚Ä¢ $z$-axis: out of the page, positive for counter-clockwise rotations ($\mathbf k$).

At an arbitrary instant  
‚Ä¢ The string makes an angle $\theta_{1}$ with the downward vertical;  
‚Ä¢ The rod makes an angle $\theta_{2}$ with the downward vertical;  
‚Ä¢ Counter-clockwise angles are positive.  

Kinematic data  
‚Ä¢ $\omega_{1} = \dot\theta_{1}$ is the angular velocity of the string about $O$;  
‚Ä¢ $\omega_{2}$ is the angular velocity of the rod about its centre of mass $C$;  
‚Ä¢ $\alpha_{1} = \dot\omega_{1}$ and $\alpha_{2} = \dot\omega_{2}$ are the corresponding angular accelerations.  

Mechanical data  
‚Ä¢ The string is mass-less and always taut, exerting only a tension $T$ along $OB$.  
‚Ä¢ The rod is rigid and uniform; its moment of inertia about an axis through $C$ normal to the plane is  
‚ÄÉ‚ÄÉ$I_{C} = \dfrac{1}{12}\,m\,l_{2}^{2}$.  
‚Ä¢ The only external forces acting on the rod are its weight $m\mathbf g = -mg\,\mathbf j$ and the tension $\mathbf T$ applied at $B$.

The task is to express the rod‚Äôs angular acceleration $\alpha_{2}$ solely in terms of $m,\,g,\,l_{1},\,l_{2},\,\theta_{1},\,\theta_{2},\,\omega_{1},\,\omega_{2}$.

---

### Step 1‚ÄÇKinematics of points $B$ and $C$
Principles / Original Formulas / Assumptions  
\[\boxed{\mathbf r_{B}=l_{1}\bigl(\sin\theta_{1}\,\mathbf i-\cos\theta_{1}\,\mathbf j\bigr)}\]  
\[\boxed{\mathbf r_{C}=\mathbf r_{B}+\dfrac{l_{2}}{2}\bigl(\sin\theta_{2}\,\mathbf i-\cos\theta_{2}\,\mathbf j\bigr)}\]  
\[\boxed{\mathbf a_{B}=\mathbf a_{C}+\boldsymbol\alpha_{2}\times(\mathbf r_{B}-\mathbf r_{C})+\boldsymbol\omega_{2}\times\!\bigl(\boldsymbol\omega_{2}\times(\mathbf r_{B}-\mathbf r_{C})\bigr)}\]

Derivation  
\[
\begin{align}
\mathbf r_{B}&=l_{1}\!\bigl(\sin\theta_{1}\,\mathbf i-\cos\theta_{1}\,\mathbf j\bigr),\label{eq:rB}\tag{1}\\
\mathbf r_{C}&=\mathbf r_{B}+\frac{l_{2}}{2}\!\bigl(\sin\theta_{2}\,\mathbf i-\cos\theta_{2}\,\mathbf j\bigr).\label{eq:rC}\tag{2}
\end{align}
\]

Differentiate twice with respect to time to obtain the absolute acceleration of $B$ produced by the motion of the string:
\[
\begin{align}
\mathbf a_{B}&=l_{1}\!\left(\alpha_{1}\cos\theta_{1}-\omega_{1}^{2}\sin\theta_{1}\right)\mathbf i
              +l_{1}\!\left(\alpha_{1}\sin\theta_{1}+\omega_{1}^{2}\cos\theta_{1}\right)\mathbf j,
\qquad\alpha_{1}\equiv\dot\omega_{1}.\label{eq:aBstring}\tag{3}
\end{align}
\]

For the rod, write $\mathbf r_{B}-\mathbf r_{C}=-\dfrac{l_{2}}{2}\bigl(\sin\theta_{2}\,\mathbf i-\cos\theta_{2}\,\mathbf j\bigr)$.  
Using the rigid-body acceleration theorem,
\[
\begin{align}
\mathbf a_{B}
      &=\mathbf a_{C}-\frac{l_{2}}{2}\alpha_{2}\!\bigl(\cos\theta_{2}\,\mathbf i+\sin\theta_{2}\,\mathbf j\bigr)
        +\frac{l_{2}}{2}\omega_{2}^{2}\!\bigl(\sin\theta_{2}\,\mathbf i-\cos\theta_{2}\,\mathbf j\bigr).\label{eq:aBrod}\tag{4}
\end{align}
\]

---

### Step 2‚ÄÇTranslational and rotational dynamics of the rod
Principles / Original Formulas / Assumptions  
\[\boxed{\sum\mathbf F = m\,\mathbf a_{C}}\]  
\[\boxed{\sum\tau_{C}=I_{C}\alpha_{2}}\]

Derivation  
Tension acts along $BO$ towards $O$:
\[
\mathbf T=-T\sin\theta_{1}\,\mathbf i+T\cos\theta_{1}\,\mathbf j.\notag
\]

(i) Translational motion of the centre of mass:
\[
\begin{align}
m a_{Cx}&=-T\sin\theta_{1},\label{eq:transx}\tag{5}\\
m a_{Cy}&=T\cos\theta_{1}-mg.\label{eq:transy}\tag{6}
\end{align}
\]

(ii) Rotational motion about $C$.  
Because the weight acts through $C$, only tension produces torque:
\[
\begin{align}
I_{C}\alpha_{2}&=(\mathbf r_{B}-\mathbf r_{C})\times\mathbf T
               =\frac{l_{2}}{2}T\sin\!\bigl(\theta_{1}-\theta_{2}\bigr),\notag \\
\Longrightarrow\quad
\alpha_{2}&=\frac{6T}{m\,l_{2}}\sin\!\bigl(\theta_{1}-\theta_{2}\bigr).\label{eq:alpha2T}\tag{7}
\end{align}
\]

---

### Step 3‚ÄÇCompatibility of the two expressions for $\mathbf a_{B}$
Principles / Original Formulas / Assumptions  
\[\boxed{\mathbf a_{B}\ \text{from (\ref{eq:aBstring}) equals that from (\ref{eq:aBrod})}}\]

Derivation  
Equating $x$-components of (\ref{eq:aBstring}) and (\ref{eq:aBrod}) and using (\ref{eq:transx}):
\[
\begin{align}
l_{1}\!\left(\alpha_{1}\cos\theta_{1}-\omega_{1}^{2}\sin\theta_{1}\right)
&=-\frac{T}{m}\sin\theta_{1}-\frac{l_{2}}{2}\alpha_{2}\cos\theta_{2}
  +\frac{l_{2}}{2}\omega_{2}^{2}\sin\theta_{2}.\label{eq:xcomp}\tag{8}
\end{align}
\]

Equating $y$-components and using (\ref{eq:transy}):
\[
\begin{align}
l_{1}\!\left(\alpha_{1}\sin\theta_{1}+\omega_{1}^{2}\cos\theta_{1}\right)
&=\frac{T}{m}\cos\theta_{1}-g-\frac{l_{2}}{2}\alpha_{2}\sin\theta_{2}
  -\frac{l_{2}}{2}\omega_{2}^{2}\cos\theta_{2}.\label{eq:ycomp}\tag{9}
\end{align}
\]

---

### Step 4‚ÄÇElimination of $\alpha_{1}$ and solution for the tension $T$
Principles / Original Formulas / Assumptions  
\[\boxed{(\ref{eq:ycomp})\cos\theta_{1}-(\ref{eq:xcomp})\sin\theta_{1}}\]

Derivation  
Combining the two equations as indicated removes $\alpha_{1}$:
\[
\begin{align}
l_{1}\omega_{1}^{2}
  &=\frac{T}{m}-g\cos\theta_{1}
    +\frac{l_{2}}{2}\alpha_{2}\sin\!\bigl(\theta_{1}-\theta_{2}\bigr)
    -\frac{l_{2}}{2}\omega_{2}^{2}\cos\!\bigl(\theta_{1}-\theta_{2}\bigr).\label{eq:Tstep1}\tag{10}
\end{align}
\]

Insert $\alpha_{2}$ from (\ref{eq:alpha2T}):
\[
\begin{align}
l_{1}\omega_{1}^{2}
  &=\frac{T}{m}-g\cos\theta_{1}
    +\frac{l_{2}}{2}\,\frac{6T}{m\,l_{2}}\sin^{2}\!\bigl(\theta_{1}-\theta_{2}\bigr)
    -\frac{l_{2}}{2}\omega_{2}^{2}\cos\!\bigl(\theta_{1}-\theta_{2}\bigr), \nonumber\\
\Bigl(1+3\sin^{2}\!\bigl(\theta_{1}-\theta_{2}\bigr)\Bigr)\frac{T}{m}
  &=g\cos\theta_{1}+l_{1}\omega_{1}^{2}
    +\frac{l_{2}}{2}\omega_{2}^{2}\cos\!\bigl(\theta_{1}-\theta_{2}\bigr). \nonumber
\end{align}
\]

Thus
\[
\begin{align}
T
  =m\,
    \frac{g\cos\theta_{1}+l_{1}\omega_{1}^{2}
          +\dfrac{l_{2}}{2}\omega_{2}^{2}\cos(\theta_{1}-\theta_{2})}
         {1+3\sin^{2}(\theta_{1}-\theta_{2})}.\label{eq:Tfinal}\tag{11}
\end{align}
\]

---

### Step 5‚ÄÇRod‚Äôs angular acceleration $\alpha_{2}$
Principles / Original Formulas / Assumptions  
\[\boxed{\alpha_{2}=\dfrac{6T}{m\,l_{2}}\sin(\theta_{1}-\theta_{2})}\]

Derivation  
Substitute (\ref{eq:Tfinal}) into (\ref{eq:alpha2T}):
\[
\begin{align}
\alpha_{2}
&=\frac{6\sin(\theta_{1}-\theta_{2})}{l_{2}}
   \frac{g\cos\theta_{1}+l_{1}\omega_{1}^{2}
         +\dfrac{l_{2}}{2}\omega_{2}^{2}\cos(\theta_{1}-\theta_{2})}
        {1+3\sin^{2}(\theta_{1}-\theta_{2})}, \nonumber\\[4pt]
&=\frac{3\sin(\theta_{1}-\theta_{2})\,
        \Bigl[2g\cos\theta_{1}+2l_{1}\omega_{1}^{2}
               +l_{2}\omega_{2}^{2}\cos(\theta_{1}-\theta_{2})\Bigr]}
        {l_{2}\,\bigl[1+3\sin^{2}(\theta_{1}-\theta_{2})\bigr]}.\label{eq:alpha2final}\tag{12}
\end{align}
\]

---

### Final Answer
\[
\begin{align}
\boxed{\displaystyle
\alpha_{2}
=\frac{3\,\sin(\theta_{1}-\theta_{2})\,
        \Bigl[2g\cos\theta_{1}+2l_{1}\omega_{1}^{2}
               +l_{2}\omega_{2}^{2}\cos(\theta_{1}-\theta_{2})\Bigr]}
       {\,l_{2}\Bigl[1+3\sin^{2}(\theta_{1}-\theta_{2})\Bigr]}}
\end{align}
\]

# Refined Solution
### Problem Statement Explanation
We study a Newtonian three‚Äìbody system that consists of  

1. A binary star (‚ÄúKepler-49‚Äù) made of  
   ‚Ä¢ star Saka with mass \(M_{S}\),  
   ‚Ä¢ star Juipte with mass \(M_{J}\).  
   They move on coplanar, circular orbits about their common centre of mass (COM) with constant angular frequency \(\Omega\).  
   The orbital radii from the COM are \(R_{S}\) and \(R_{J}\); the instantaneous separation is \(R_{0}=R_{S}+R_{J}\).

2. A distant planet of mass \(m\;(m\ll M_{S},M_{J})\) whose orbital size \(r\) obeys \(R_{0}\ll r\).  
   During one binary period \(T_{\rm bin}=2\pi/\Omega\) the planet‚Äôs position is almost unchanged, so it experiences the time‚Äìaveraged binary potential  

   \[
   V(r)=V_{0}(r)+\delta V(r),\qquad 
   V_{0}(r)=-\frac{G(M_{S}+M_{J})m}{r},\qquad 
   \bigl|\delta V\bigr|\ll|V_{0}|.
   \]

The planet‚Äôs total energy satisfies \(E<0\); its (conserved) orbital angular momentum magnitude is denoted \(L\) (the symbol \(\bar L\) in the original statement).  

For the pure inverse‚Äìsquare part \(V_{0}\) the Laplace‚ÄìRunge‚ÄìLenz (LRL) vector  

\[
\vec B=\vec v\times\vec L-G(M_{S}+M_{J})m\,\hat r
\]

is conserved; it points toward the periapsis (closest point) of the Keplerian ellipse.  
Adding \(\delta V\propto r^{-3}\) breaks that exact conservation; the slow rotation of \(\vec B\) produces a periapsis advance (orbital precession) \(\Delta\alpha\) per revolution, whose leading value in the small ratio \(R_{0}/r\) is required in terms of \(M_{S},M_{J},G,\Omega,m,L\).

Plane motion is assumed throughout; relativistic corrections and planetary self-gravity are neglected.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
### Step 1 ‚Äì Geometry and dynamics of the binary stars  
Principles / Original Formulas / Assumptions  
\[\boxed{M_{S}R_{S}=M_{J}R_{J}}\]  
\[\boxed{\displaystyle \frac{G\,M_{S}M_{J}}{R_{0}^{2}}
         =M_{S}R_{S}\Omega^{2}=M_{J}R_{J}\Omega^{2}}\]

\[
\begin{align}
\text{From the COM condition:}\qquad 
R_{S}&=\frac{M_{J}}{M_{S}+M_{J}}\,R_{0},&
R_{J}&= \frac{M_{S}}{M_{S}+M_{J}}\,R_{0}, \\[6pt]
\text{From the force balance:}\qquad 
R_{0}^{3}&=\frac{G\bigl(M_{S}+M_{J}\bigr)}{\Omega^{2}}
\;\;\Longrightarrow\;\;
R_{0}= \Bigl[\tfrac{G(M_{S}+M_{J})}{\Omega^{2}}\Bigr]^{1/3}.
\label{eq:R0}\tag{1}
\end{align}
\]

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
### Step 2 ‚Äì Time-averaged potential felt by the distant planet  
Principles / Original Formulas / Assumptions  
\[\boxed{V(\vec r,t)= -\frac{G M_{S}m}{|\vec r-\vec R_{S}(t)|}
                     -\frac{G M_{J}m}{|\vec r-\vec R_{J}(t)|}}\]  
\[\boxed{\displaystyle \frac{1}{|\vec r-\vec R|}
        =\frac{1}{r}
         +\frac{\vec R\!\cdot\!\hat r}{r^{2}}
         +\frac{3(\vec R\!\cdot\!\hat r)^{2}-R^{2}}{2r^{3}}
         +\mathcal O\!\bigl(R^{3}/r^{4}\bigr)}\]

\[
\begin{align}
\overline{V}(r)
&= -\frac{G(M_{S}+M_{J})m}{r}
   -\frac{Gm}{4r^{3}}
     \bigl[M_{S}R_{S}^{2}+M_{J}R_{J}^{2}\bigr]
   +\mathcal O(R_{0}^{4}/r^{5}). \nonumber \\[4pt]
\therefore\;
\delta V(r)
&= -\frac{Gm}{4r^{3}}
     \bigl[M_{S}R_{S}^{2}+M_{J}R_{J}^{2}\bigr]
   \;=\;
   -\frac{G M_{S}M_{J}m}{4\,\bigl(M_{S}+M_{J}\bigr)}
    \frac{R_{0}^{2}}{r^{3}}
    \;\equiv\;-\frac{C}{r^{3}},
\label{eq:deltaV}\tag{2}
\end{align}
\]
where  
\[
C=\frac{G M_{S}M_{J}m}{4\,(M_{S}+M_{J})}\,R_{0}^{2}.
\label{eq:Cdef}\tag{3}
\]

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
### Step 3 ‚Äì Unperturbed Keplerian orbit of the planet  
Principles / Original Formulas / Assumptions  
\[\boxed{r(\theta)=\dfrac{p}{1+e\cos\theta}}\]  
\[\boxed{p=\dfrac{L^{2}}{G(M_{S}+M_{J})m^{2}},\qquad
        e=\sqrt{1+\dfrac{2EL^{2}}
                         {G^{2}(M_{S}+M_{J})^{2}m^{3}}}}\]

\[
\begin{align}
u(\theta)\equiv\frac1r
  &=\frac{1+e\cos\theta}{p},&
r(\theta)
  &=\frac{p}{1+e\cos\theta}.
\label{eq:orbit}\tag{4}
\end{align}
\]

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
### Step 4 ‚Äì LRL vector for the unperturbed motion  
Principles / Original Formulas / Assumptions  
\[\boxed{\vec B=\vec v\times\vec L-G(M_{S}+M_{J})m\,\hat r}\]  
\[\boxed{\displaystyle\frac{d\vec B}{dt}=0\quad(V=V_{0})}\]

\[
\begin{align}
|\vec B_{0}|
&=G(M_{S}+M_{J})m\,e.
\label{eq:B0mag}\tag{5}
\end{align}
\]
We orient the coordinate axes so that \(\vec B_{0}\) points along \(+\hat x\); consequently the periapsis occurs at polar angle \(\theta=0\).

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
### Step 5 ‚Äì Instantaneous change of \(\vec B\) caused by \(\delta V\)  
Principles / Original Formulas / Assumptions  
\[\boxed{\delta V(r)= -\dfrac{C}{r^{3}}}\]  
\[\boxed{\vec F_{\delta}=-\nabla(\delta V)}\]  
\[\boxed{\displaystyle\frac{d\vec B}{dt}= \frac{1}{m}\bigl(\vec F_{\delta}\times\vec L\bigr)}\]  
\[\boxed{\displaystyle \dot\theta=\frac{L}{m r^{2}}}\]

\[
\begin{align}
\vec F_{\delta}
   &= -\frac{d}{dr}\!\Bigl(-\frac{C}{r^{3}}\Bigr)\hat r
    =-\frac{3C}{r^{4}}\hat r,\\[6pt]
\frac{d\vec B}{dt}
   &=\frac{1}{m}\bigl(\vec F_{\delta}\times\vec L\bigr)
    =\frac{1}{m}\Bigl(-\frac{3C}{r^{4}}\hat r\Bigr)\times\bigl(L\hat z\bigr)
    =\frac{3CL}{m r^{4}}\;\hat\theta,\\[6pt]
\frac{d\vec B}{d\theta}
   &=\frac{d\vec B/dt}{\dot\theta}
    =\frac{3CL}{m r^{4}}
      \frac{m r^{2}}{L}
    =\frac{3C}{r^{2}}\;\hat\theta.
\label{eq:dBdtheta}\tag{6}
\end{align}
\]

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
### Step 6 ‚Äì Cumulative change \(\Delta\vec B\) over one orbit  
Principles / Original Formulas / Assumptions  
\[\boxed{r(\theta)=\dfrac{p}{1+e\cos\theta}}\]  
\[\boxed{\hat\theta=(-\sin\theta,\;\cos\theta,\;0)}\]

\[
\begin{align}
\frac{d\vec B}{d\theta}
  &=\frac{3C}{r^{2}}\hat\theta
   =\frac{3C}{p^{2}}\bigl(1+e\cos\theta\bigr)^{2}\hat\theta, \\[6pt]
\Delta\vec B
  &=\int_{0}^{2\pi}\!\frac{d\vec B}{d\theta}\,d\theta
   =\frac{3C}{p^{2}}
     \int_{0}^{2\pi}\!
       \bigl(1+e\cos\theta\bigr)^{2}
       (-\sin\theta\,\hat x+\cos\theta\,\hat y)\,d\theta. \nonumber
\end{align}
\]
Only the \(\hat y\)-component survives; performing the integral  
\(\displaystyle\int_{0}^{2\pi}(1+e\cos\theta)^{2}\cos\theta\,d\theta=2\pi e\), we obtain
\[
\begin{align}
\Delta\vec B
  &=\frac{6\pi e\,C}{p^{2}}\;\hat y.
\label{eq:DeltaB}\tag{7}
\end{align}
\]

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
### Step 7 ‚Äì Periapsis advance per revolution  
Principles / Original Formulas / Assumptions  
\[\boxed{\displaystyle
\Delta\alpha\;\approx\;
\frac{|\vec B_{0}\times\Delta\vec B|}
     {|\vec B_{0}|^{2}}
\quad(\text{first order in }\Delta\vec B)}\]

\[
\begin{align}
\vec B_{0}\parallel\hat x,\;
\Delta\vec B\parallel\hat y
 \;\Longrightarrow\;
|\vec B_{0}\times\Delta\vec B|
  &=|\vec B_{0}|\;|\Delta\vec B|, \\[6pt]
\therefore\;
\Delta\alpha
  &=\frac{|\Delta\vec B|}{|\vec B_{0}|}
   =\frac{\dfrac{6\pi e\,C}{p^{2}}}
          {G(M_{S}+M_{J})m\,e}
   =\frac{6\pi\,C}{G(M_{S}+M_{J})m\,p^{2}}. \label{eq:alpha1}\tag{8a}
\end{align}
\]

Insert \(C\) from \eqref{eq:Cdef} and \(p\) from \eqref{eq:orbit}:

\[
\begin{align}
C &=\frac{G M_{S}M_{J}m}{4\,(M_{S}+M_{J})}\,R_{0}^{2},\\
p^{2} &=\frac{L^{4}}{G^{2}(M_{S}+M_{J})^{2}m^{4}}.
\nonumber
\end{align}
\]

\[
\begin{align}
\Delta\alpha
 &=\frac{6\pi}{G(M_{S}+M_{J})m}
    \;\frac{G M_{S}M_{J}m}{4\,(M_{S}+M_{J})}\,R_{0}^{2}
    \;\frac{G^{2}(M_{S}+M_{J})^{2}m^{4}}{L^{4}} \\[6pt]
 &=\frac{3\pi}{2}\,
    \frac{G^{2}M_{S}M_{J}m^{4}}{L^{4}}
    \,R_{0}^{2}. \label{eq:alpha2}\tag{8b}
\end{align}
\]

Finally substitute \(R_{0}^{2}\) from \eqref{eq:R0}:

\[
